						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tomaitheous wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">lidnariq wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Careful -- you'll need an active rectifier, not a passive one; a conventional 4-diode full-wave rectifier will, even if you use Schottky diodes, drop the center .4V out of your 1Vpp signal.</div> Thanks for the tip. So you mean a 0.4v in the form of a shift/offset or do you mean the whole range will be scaled resulting in the difference? (I think the latter. 'Cause there's a voltage drop a diode?</div> Right, but what will happen is a signal that started off like<div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">&nbsp;_.-._<br />/&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; \&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; /<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; `-.-`<br /></div>will end up looking like<div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">__.-.__&nbsp; &nbsp; ___<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;`-`<br /></div>i.e. not a sine wave anymore, and signals less than 0.4Vpp are lost entirely. It's called dead-band distortion if that helps.<div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"> Also, I found this link: <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://zone.ni.com/devzone/cda/tut/p/id/4750">http://zone.ni.com/devzone/cda/tut/p/id/4750</a><!-- m --> . It states sync to white level is 1v. White level, not peak level. Peak level is listed as 120 IRE for NTSC-U and 133 IRE for PAL. Funny thing about NTSC-J, is that it shares the same IRE 0 for black starting point. So maybe Peak level for NTSC-J is the same as PAL too.</div>Yes, US NTSC is the one one with the silly black level thing.<div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">This still doesn't answer some questions. If IRE 100 is in face 0.714v and sync+IRE 100 = 1v, then IRE 120 or 133 pushes the max range past 1v (assuming sync level stays the same). Or is IRE 120/133 the max 0.714 level?</div>They're talking about the maximum chroma (max amplitude = 60IRE) in addition to full luma (100IRE). But you can't have maximum chroma on a full-white signal (per the RGB&lt;-&gt;YIQ conversion) so it's something less -- apparently 120IRE.<div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Which leads me to another question. How to represent <em>whiter than white</em> on a RGB 24bit? Do you simply scale down and adjust for this (which makes the whole range darker)? Or do you decode YCrCb at those values, THEN clamp to 0 or 255? I'm thinking it's the latter. You might not be able to show Luma only whiter-than-white, but it should effect the color decoding of the other two channels.</div>I'd clip after converting colorspaces. Depending on context, I might instead use a 30 or 48 bit linear colorspace, or the 48-bit "half float" if I needed even more dynamic range.</div>

